\title{Topological Anderson Insulators with Two Types of Chiral Edge States}
\author{Ying Su$^{1,2}$}
\author{Y. Avishai$^{3,4}$}
\author{X. R. Wang$^{1,2}$}
\affiliation{$^{1}$Physics Department, The Hong Kong University of
Science and Technology, Clear Water Bay, Kowloon, Hong Kong}
\affiliation{$^{2}$HKUST Shenzhen Research Institute, Shenzhen 518057,
China}
\affiliation{$^{3}$Department of Physics, Ben-Gurion University of
the Negev, Beer-Sheva, Israel}
\affiliation{$^{4}$Department of Physics, NYU-Shanghai University, Shanghai, China}
\date{\today}

\begin{abstract}
Occurrence of topological Anderson insulator (TAI) in HgTe quantum well demonstrates that topological phase (TP)
transition can be driven by disorder. Numerical simulations indicate that the re-entrant $2e^2/h$ quantized conductance of a TAI is contributed by helical edge states. Within a certain extension of the Kane-Mele model with site disorder,
 it is shown here that the physics of TAI becomes even richer. 



The model exhibits robust chiral edge states with both opposite-spin
and single-spin polarization, in respective analogies with the quantum hall and quantum anomalous hall effects. Moreover, tuning either disorder or Fermi energy in both topologically trivial and nontrivial phases, drives transitions between these two distinct TAI phases, marked by a jump of the quantized conductance from $e^2/h$ to $2 e^2/h$. Thus, disorder induces a spin nondegenerate TP transition and results in TAI with different spin polarized chiral edge states. In order to understand the underlying mechanism, we introduce an effective medium theory based on the self-consistent Born approximation. It yields an accurate description of different TAIs
 that occupy different regions in parameter space.
\end{abstract}


\vspace{-0.2in}
\maketitle



{\it Introduction.}---The physics related to electron properties in topological insulators stirred intense experimental and theoretical studies\cite{T1,T11,T2,T3,T4,T5,T6,T7,T9}. Observations of quantized conductances at $2e^2/h$ in time reversal invariant topological insulators \cite{T3,T4} and $e^2/h$ in magnetically
doped topological insulators \cite{T9} respectively confirm the occurrence of the quantum spin Hall (QSH) and the quantum anomalous Hall (QAH) effects. A well accepted paradigm is that the main distinction between topological and trivial insulators is the existence (in the former) of topologically protected gapless edge states 
that conduct (either charge or spin) even at strong disorder. However, this statement is somewhat questioned as it has recently been found that the two-dimensional topological insulators (the HgTe quantum well and Kane-Mele model) in the trivial phase and with strong disorder, supports robust helical edge states, which contribute to a quantized conductance (as a function of disorder strength) at value $2e^2/h$ \cite{TAI1,TAI2,TAI3,TAI4,TAI5}. Hence, this phase is evidently not trivial, and termed as {\it topological Anderson insulator} (TAI). An effective medium theory based on the self-consistent Born approximation demonstrates that in fact, disorder can effectively modify the topological mass and chemical potential of HgTe quantum well, and drive a TP transition \cite{TAI6}. TAI in three dimensions has also been identified in a cubic lattice in which electrons are subject to strong spin-orbit coupling (SOC) \cite{TAI7}.

In the present work, the roles of spin and valley degeneracies in TAI 
are elucidated and shown to substantially enrich the underlying physics. 
The starting point is a model where electrons live on a hexagonal lattice,  subject to SOC, staggered sublattice potential, antiferromagnetic exchange field \cite{AFM1,AFM2,AFM3,AFM4}, and off-resonant circularly polarized light \cite{L1,L2,L3}. In the absence of disorder, this model exhibits numerous TPs including the quantum Hall trio \cite{QHtri}: The quantum Hall (QH), (without external magnetic field), the QSH, and the QAH effects. After adding site 
disorder (with fluctuation strength $W$), the two-terminal conductance $G$ is studied at a given Fermi energy $E_F$ in the QH, QAH, and the trivial [normal insulating (NI)] phases, and displayed in the $W-E_F$ plane. 
 In all three phases, the conductance initially decays as $W$ increases from 0, but then it increases and reaches


 quantized values at $2e^2/h$ or $e^2/h$ (depending on the Fermi energy and disorder). Naturally, the conductance finally vanishes at strong enough disorder. Existence of nonequilibrium local spin current (NLSC) in the different nontrivial TAI phases confirms the conjecture that these two quantized conductance plateaus are respectively contributed by opposite-spin and single-spin polarized chiral edge states, with complete analogy with the QH and the QAH states. Thus, this model exhibits two distinct TAI phases. The transformation between these two phases can be driven by tuning either disorder or Fermi energy. 
 Our results can be easily extended to include the QSH phase and TAI in three dimensions.






