The identification of TPs with pairs of spin Chern numbers is:
 QH TP for $(\pm 1,\pm 1)$, QSH TP for $(\pm 1,\mp 1)$, QAH TP for $(\pm 1,0)$ or $(0,\pm 1)$, and trivial phase for $(0,0)$. 
The TP diagram in the $\lambda_H-\lambda_V$ plane is schematically shown in Fig. \ref{fig1}(a) and (b). For $3\sqrt{3}\lambda_{SO}>\lambda_{AM}>0$, there is a QSH TP in the center as shown in Fig. \ref{fig1}(a). For $\lambda_{AM}>3\sqrt{3} \lambda_{SO}>0$, the QSH TP disappears as shown in Fig. \ref{fig1}(b). The red (green) lines are phase boundaries where the bulk band gap closes for spin up (down) at $K$ or $K'$ valley. Crossing points between TP boundaries with the same color (different colors) indicates that the bulk band gap closes at the two different valleys for a single spin (opposite spins). Apart from these crossing points on the TP boundaries, the bulk band gap closes only at one valley for a single spin. To show these results, we choose three points on the TP boundaries as shown in Fig. \ref{fig1}(b), the corresponding low energy band structures near the two valleys are shown in Fig. \ref{fig1}(c), (d) and (e), where the red color denotes the band for spin up 
electrons and the green color denotes the band for spin down electrons.






{\it Topological Anderson insulator.}---In order to elucidate the role of edge states we now apply our model within the geometry of a long strip with zigzag edges. Assuming the SOC to be weak, we set $\lambda_{SO}=0.02t$ and $\lambda_{AM}=1.7t>3\sqrt{3} \lambda_{SO}$. The QSH TP is virtually absent and the relevant phase diagram is displayed in Fig. \ref{fig1}(b). 
Analyzing the energy spectrum of the edge modes is carried out numerically. To be concrete, we fix $t'=0.3t$ and use $(\lambda_H,\lambda_V)$ to control the properties of the various TPs (still in the absence of disorder). 
Specifically, the QH states with $(0.37t, 0.25t)$, QAH states with $(0.35t, 0.3t)$, and trivial states with $(0.31t, 0.16t)$ and $(0.28t, 0.32t)$ are studied. Their low energy band structures are shown in Fig. \ref{fig2}(a)-(d). 




\begin{figure*}
  \begin{center}
  \includegraphics[width=17 cm]{Fig3.eps}
  \end{center}
  \vspace{-0.2in}
\caption{(color online). The NLSCs for the nanoribbons in different phases and with various disorder strengths $W$ and Fermi energies $E_F$ in a two terminal setup. The upper (lower) panels stand for spin up (down). The color in each hexagon is the average value of the NLSCs on its six corners. The red (green) arrows indicate the current direction for spin up (down) projections. The arrow size is proportional to NLSC. $eV$ is the chemical potential difference between the source and drain. (a) $W=3t$ and $E_F=0.9t$ (see the red spot in Fig. \ref{fig2}(e)). (b) $W=3t$ and $E_F=0.5t$ (see the red spot in Fig. \ref{fig2}(f)). (C) $W=4t$ and $E_F=0.6t$ (see the red spot in Fig. \ref{fig2}(g)).}
  \label{fig3}
  \vspace{-0.2in}
\end{figure*}




Introducing now site disorder enables the study of Anderson localization (or its absence) along the nanoribbon in different phases. 
These are encoded through the two-terminal conductance and its behavior in the $W-E_F$ plane, as displayed in (Fig. \ref{fig2}(e)-(h)). In the QH phase (Fig.\ref{fig2} (e) and (i)), the robust edge states contribute to quantized conductance with values of $2e^2/h$ and $e^2/h$ due to mismatch of bulk band gap opening and closure for the two different spin projections. Moreover, the quantized conductance plateaus penetrate into the valence band where the conductance initially decreases to zero and then {\it as disorder increases} re-increases first to $e^2/h$ and then to $2e^2/h$. In the QAH phase (Fig.\ref{fig2} (f) and (j)), there is a single plateau of the quantized conductance in the bulk band gap at value $e^2/h$. However, conductance plateaus at values of $e^2/h$ and $2e^2/h$ occur in the valence band. Similarly, for the trivial phase, conductance plateaus at values of $e^2/h$ and $2e^2/h$ occur (due to the gap closure-opening mismatch mentioned above), only in the valence band (Fig.\ref{fig2} (g) and (k)). Furthermore, in the trivial phase (Fig.\ref{fig2} (h) and (l)), we even find quantized conductance plateau in the valence band only at $e^2/h$. Thus, from our numerical analysis we may conclude that there are two distinct TAI phases in analogy with QH and QAH phases. In addition, there is also a single trivial phase. 

